What Can A Force Do?
Force can affect an object in man y ways.
1. Force can stop a moving object– For 
example, force applied by the foot of a 
player on a moving football stops the ball.
2. Force can move a stationar y object–  For 
example, when a player applies force on 
a football by kicking it, the ball moves.
3. Force can increase or decr ease the speed of a 
moving object–  For example, when we push a 
moving object its speed increases. When we 
apply brakes in our car, its speed decr eases.
4. Force can chang e the size and shape of 
an object– For example, when a 
squee ze a toothpas te tube, its shape 
chang es.
5. Force can change the direction of a moving 
object–  For example, when a player hits a moving 
ball with a bat, the ball chang es its direction.
In other words, force can move a stationar y object and stop a moving object. It can  
also chang e the speed, direction, size and shape of an object.
Some more examples to under stand the effects of force are–

Sometimes a force does not show any effect. For example, when we apply force on 
a wall, it neither moves nor changes its shape or size.You  Know Must (Knowledge )
Types of Forces
In nature, there are two types of forces acting all the times– Gravity and Friction.
1. Gravity–  The force that pulls all objects downwards towards the centre of the 
earth is called gravity. 
For example, when we throw a ball up in the air, it first rises up, then seems to stop 
and then falls back to the ground. The ball falls back due to the force of gravity.
2. Friction–  When we push a toy car on a floor , it slows down and stops after 
some time. The force that acts on it to slow down is called the force of friction. 
Friction opposes movemen t. It occur s because of rubbing of the object 
against a rough surface. Friction is more on rough surfaces and less on 
smooth surfaces.
Friction is necessary at man y places. We can not walk on a polished surface because 
the friction is less. Without friction, we will slip and will not be able to walk.You  Know Must (Knowledge )

Advantage of Friction–
 1. Friction help s us to walk.
 2. Friction help s us to write. We can not write on polished surfaces.
 3. Friction between road and tyres of automoblies mak es their movemen t 
possible.
Disadv antages of Friction–
 1. It slows down or stops the motion of vehicles. 
 2. It produces heat which damag es the parts of machines.
 3. It damag es the soles of our shoes and tyres of vehicles.
Thus, we can say that friction has man y disadv antages but it is necessar y for 
movemen t.

Let'sKnow Let'sKnowA machine is a device or a tool which help s us to do work easily , efficien tly and 
fast. Before the invention of sewing machine, people stitched their clothes by 
hand. It was difficult and time consuming. A sewing machine has made 
stitching easier and faster. A knife, scissor s, tweezers etc. also help to mak e 
our work easier and faster. They come under simple machines. Big machines 
like washing machines, cranes, cars, bulldo zers etc. are comple x machines 
made by joining man y simple machines. In this chap ter, we shall learn about 
the simple machines.
Simple Machines
Simple machines do work either by changing the direction of force or by reducing 
the effort needed. Ther e are six types of simple machines-the lever, the pulle y, the 
inclined plane, the wedge, the wheel and axle, and the screw.
The lever , the inclined plane and the wedge are the oldest known 
machines.You  Know Must (Knowledge )
Environmental Studies-5 114

! A lever is a simple machine which consis ts of a load, fulcrum and Lever– 
effort. The load is the object that is being moved or lifted. The fulcrum is the 
central poin t and the effort is the force requir ed to lift or move the load.
 A lever can help to lift up heavy loads and open or 
separ ate things. See-sa w is an example of lever, 
when force is applied to one side, it is pushed 
down and the other side lifts up.
 A hammer ,a bottle opener , a crowbar and a pair 
of scissor s etc. are examples of lever.
! A Pulle y is a simple machine made with a Pulle y– 
rope or chain wrapped around a wheel. It chang es 
the direction of force and mak es it easier to lift things 
to some heigh t. Pulle ys are used in drawing water 
from a w ell, r aising a flag on a flagpole, lifting hea vy 
weigh ts by a crane etc. 
!  An inclined plane is the Inclined plane–
sloping or a slanting surface which connects a 
lower level to a higher level. It help s to move 
heavier objects to a heigh t easily . Childr en's 
slides in a playground, ramp s for wheelchair s, 
sloping roads etc. are some examples of 
inclined plane. 
! A wedge is a pair of two inclined planes Wedge– 
attached back to back forming a sharp edge. This 
egde can slice things apart. For example- knife, an  
axe, a razor or a chisel. 
!  A wheel and axle arrangemen t is Wheel and axle–
a simple machine in which a wheel rotates around 
the centre or axle. An axle is usually a smaller 
wheel attached at the centre of a larger wheel.
Environmental Studies-5115

A wheel is not a machine by itself . The wheel and axle mus t move together to 
form a simple machine. Some common examples of wheel and axle are- tyres 
of vehicles, screwdrivers, door knob s, rolling skates, electric fans, Merr y- go -
round at a fun fair etc. 
 A screw is commonly used for holding things together more firmly so that 
they can't be forced to separ ate. Screws are also used for lifting heavy things.
  A Screw Jack is used to lift a car to chang e its tyre. For example–! A scr ew look s like a nail with gr ooves cut in it. It Screw– 
has a winding edge called a thread. The winding edge of 
the screw is actually an inclined plane wound on a rod.

Let'sKnow Let'sKnowA house is one of the basic needs of human beings. It protects us from harsh 
weather, theft and animals. Different types of houses or shelt ers are seen at 
different places because of the factors like clima te of that place, availability of 
building materials, economic status of the house owner etc.Starter
! Can you recognise this house?
! Wha t is it made of?
! Wher e is it found?
According to Location and Climate
Hilly Regions– Hilly regions receiv e heavy 
rain and snowfall. These houses usually have 
sloping roofs. This prevents rainwater and 
snow from accumula ting  on roofs and sliding 
off easily from the roofs. Besides, stones are 
easily available there. Hence, stones are  
mos tly used to build houses in these areas.
Polar Regions– In polar regions, the land is 
always covered with ice and snow. The people 
living there called Eskimos,build their  houses 
with the block s of ice and snow. These houses 
are called igloos . The floor or an igloo is covered 
with animal skin to keep it warm.
Environmental Studies-5 120

Earthquak e Prone Regions– In earthquak e prone 
regions like Japan, houses are made up of 
bamboo and wood. These houses cause much 
less damage even if they collapse during an 
Flood Prone Regions– Houses in flood prone areas 
are made on raised platforms, supported by 
wooden pillar s called stilts. Stilts keep the house 
safe from flood wate r. Stilt houses also have 
sloping roofs to allow rainwater to drain off easily .
Hot Regions– In places such as Rajas than, wher e 
the clima te is very hot, people build houses with 
thick walls, plastered with mud. Their roofs are 
covered with straw or other plan t material to save 
the roof from being heated due to sun.
Temporary Houses– Soldiers, scouts and 
moun taineer s have to move from one place to 
another . They live in tempor ary houses known as 
tents. Tents are easy to carry as they are made up 
of a cloth called canvas. Nomads also live in tents.
Houseboats are mov able houses that are mostly common in the lakes of 
Kashmir and Kerala.You  Know Must (Knowledge )
Environmental Studies-5121
According to material Available
When building a house, it is better to use materials that are easily available locally. 
Ther e are two types of houses, based on the material used in them.
Kutcha Houses– Kutcha houses are common in 
villag es, These are made up of bamboo , mud, 
straw, wood and dry leaves. The floor s are usually 
made of clay and coated with cowdung.

Pucc a Houses– Pucc a houses are mos tly  found in cities 
and towns. These houses are more durable. They are 
built of brick s, stones, tiles, iron, glass, marble and 
cemen t. All these materials are easily available in cities 
and town. These houses are more expensiv e. 
Pucc a houses ar e of diff erent types–
1. Bungalows– Large single-storey 
houses with man y rooms, a lawn and a 
porch are called bung alows.
2. Multi storey buildings– In big cities, due to 
short age of space, tall-buildings with man y floor s 
are construct ed. These buildings ar e called multi- 
storey buildings. These buildings have a number of 
houses on each floor . Each of these houses is 
called a flat or an apartmen t. 
Animals Shelters
Just as people need houses to live in, animals also need a suitable shelt er to protect 
themselv es from heat ,cold ,rain and to lay eggs, etc.
! Some animals live in natural shelt ers. Lion, bear , etc live in dens. Elephan ts, 
rhinocer ose etc.  live in open or under a tree.
! Some animals mak e their homes. Birds mak e their nests, rabbits dig burr ows, 
mice dig holes etc.
Environmental Studies-5 122

ŸAccumula te  – To collect
ŸCollap se   – To fall.
ŸStilts    – Wooden pillar s
ŸCanvas   – A thick and strong cloth.Key termsKey termsKey terms! Some animals live in shelt ers made by human beings. Cows and buffaloes live 
in a shed, dogs live in kennels, horses live in stables, hens live in coops, etc
! Some animals live in water like frogs, fish, turtles, crabs, starfish, octopuses, 
whales, dolphins, etc.
! Some animals fly in air and rest on trees. e.g. birds.
!  Ants live in ant-hills. Bees live in  hives.
ŸA house is one of the basic needs of human beings.
Ÿ The location, clima te, availability of material and economic condition of 
people determine the type of house they live in.
Ÿ Animals also need a shelt er to live in.

Forest and Tribal Life18
A lar ge area of land wher e numer ous tr ees and bushes gr ow on their o wn is 
called a forest. Forests are very import ant natural resour ce.
Ÿ They help in purific ation of air. They give us oxygen.
Ÿ They prevent soil erosion.
Ÿ They give us useful products such as wood, resin, medicines, lac, fruits and 
leaves etc.
Ÿ They support a large variety of life-forms such as humans, animals, birds 
etc.
Besides, man y people are also dependen t on the forests for their survival and 
livelihood.Let'sKnow Let'sKnowUnit–VIII : Community Life
Environmental Studies-5 126

Tribes of Different States
Tribes live in different parts of India with different traditions, cultur es and 
languag es. They can be seen in Madh ya Pradesh, Odisha, Chha ttisgarh, West 
Beng al, Manipur , Nagaland, Meghala ya, Uttarakhand, Andaman and Nicobar 
islands etc. Some well-kno wn tribes are—
Bodos— They belong to Assam. Their main 
occupa tion is tea plan tation and they are the 
best craftsmen of bamboo.Tribals of India
India is one of the ten mos t forest-rich countries of the world. Besides plan ts and 
animals, forests are home to man y people 
too. The people who live in or near the 
forests and are totally dependen t on forests 
for their survival are known as Adiv asis or 
Tribal people. India is a home to about 437 
tribal communities. These tribal people play 
a major role in forming the cultur al herit age 
of India. The y are consider ed to be the true 
inhabit ants of India.
The adivasis depend on forests for food, 
shelt er and fuel. They collect fruits, nuts, berries and edible roots and hunt animals 
for food. They mak e clothes from the skin of animals. Wood is used as fuel and to 
mak e boats.
The adivasis use leaves, bark s, gum, lac etc. to mak e useful items like bask ets, mats, 
bows and arrows,  ropes etc. They also use them to construct their shelt ers in the 
forests. The tribal women use grass, seeds, flowers, shells and beads to beautif y 
themselv es . By using these things they mak e ornamen ts like bracele ts, necklaces, 
earrings etc.
Environmental Studies-5127

Gonds— They are one of the largest tribes in 
India. They are found in Madh ya Pradesh, 
Andhra Pradesh and Odisha. Their main 
occupa tion is farming and cattle rearing.
Mundas— They are found in West Beng al, 
Odisha, Jharkhand and Bihar. Their main 
occupa tion is wood cutting and fishing.
Santhals— They are found in Assam, Tripur a 
and Bihar . Their main occupa tion is farming. 
They are also involved in hunting and fishing.
Religion
The tribals are very religious. They express their faith and religion through art and 
craft. They worship the forces of nature like sun, soil, tree, animals etc. Every tribal 
community has some special trees and animals which are consider ed sacred. 
These are protected and worshipped.
Some patches of forests are worshipped and are called sacred groves. These groves 
are belie ved to be associa ted with deities. The tribals belie ves that these groves 
protect them from epidemics, wild animals and evil spirits. In different states these 
sacred groves are known by different names like 
deobhumi, devkot, devrai etc.
Bishnois of Rajas than—  The Bishnois (a tribe of 
Rajas than) are the first in the world for whom 
preser vation of animals and plan ts is a religion. 
Guru Jambhesh war, a great ecologis t had made 
principles which included a ban on killing of 
Environmental Studies-5 128

animals and felling of trees to protect all life-forms. Amrit a Devi, a Bishnoi woman, 
is a very famous conser vationis t, who used to cling to trees to protest against their 
felling.
Protecting Tribes—  Tribal people are totally dependen t on forests. They get food, 
fuel, water, timber etc. from the forests they live in. They use bamboos and pine 
trees to mak e their huts and granaries. They mak e medicines from things such as 
resin of pine tree and the bark of the cinchona tree. Forests are an import ant part 
of their social, religious and cultur al lives. Deforestation will destroy their homes, 
livelihood and cultur e. So, to protect them and our cultur al herit age, we mus t 
protect our forests.
The Story of Chipk o Movement
In 1973, villag ers in the Alaknanda valley in 
Uttarakhand protested against the felling of 
trees in the area. When a sports goods 
manuf acturing compan y wanted to cut down 
trees, the women of the area came forward to 
prevent the felling of trees. They hugged the 
trees and refused to let go till the tree-cut ters 
left. This became popular as the Chipko 
Movemen t. Some of the famous leader s of 
Chipk o Movemen t were Sunderlal Bahuguna, Gaur a Devi, Sudesha Devi and 
Chandi Prasad Bhatt.The ministry of Tribal Affairs takes care of the welfare and 
developmen t of the tribes. It also promo tes tribal art and crafts.You  Know Must (Knowledge )
Protecting forests— The governmen t has declar ed some forests as Reser ved 
Forests, National Parks or Wildlif e Sanctuaries. Here, cutting trees, hunting and 
grazing of animals is prohibit ed. Plan ts and animals are allowed to live in their 
natural surroundings without any dang er from human beings. Some such forests 
are—
